1308–Deceased","1304–Male":"1304–Deceased","1324–Male":"1324–Deceased","1330–1396":"1330–1396","1308–Female":"1308–Deceased","1315":"1315","1304":"1304","about 1308":"about 1308","1324":"1324","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Claverley, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, England","Claveley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Casterton, Rutland, England, United Kingdom":"Casterton, Rutland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Massey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Massy</i>, a pet form of   Matthew  . Compare   Mace  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one or more of several places in Normandy, such as Macey (Manche), Massy (Seine-Maritime), Macé-sur-Orne (Orne), and La Ferté Macé (Orne).","English: variant of <b>Marsay</b> (see   Marcey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mace","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Masse</i>, probably a shortened form of <i>Matthew</i> (compare   Massey   and   Massett  ) or possibly of   Thomas  .","French and Breton (<b>Macé</b>): from the French personal name <i>Macé</i>, a vernacular form of   Mathieu   ‘Matthew’. Compare   Masse   5 and   Maze   3.","French (<b>Macé</b>): habitational name from Macé or La Ferté-Macé in Orne, the former so named from Gallo-Roman <i>Macciacum</i> (from the personal name <i>Maccius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>), the latter from the personal name <i>Macé</i> (see 2 above)."]},{"name":"Massie","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeen): variant of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Marsee","meanings":["English: altered form of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Massee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Germain.","Possibly an altered form of English   Massey  .","French (<b>Massée</b>): from the feminine form of <b>Massé</b> (see   Masse  ). This surname is rare in France."]},{"name":"Massa","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Sal, Antonio, Silvio, Annamarie, Biagio, Caesar, Carmela, Dante, Elisabetta, Ennio.","Italian: habitational name from any of various places called Massa, for example Massa Lubrense or Massa di Somma, both in Naples province, or Masse d'Albe in Aquila, all named from medieval Latin <i>massa</i> ‘farm, estate’ (from Latin <i>massa</i> ‘mass, lump, pile’, Greek <i>maza</i>). This surname is also found in southern France (see   Massey   5)."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Macey","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  .","Americanized form of Slovak and Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Macej</b> or <b>Mačej</b> and Polish   Maciej  , derivatives of the Latin personal name <i>Matthaeus</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Masey","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  ."]},{"name":"Macy","meanings":["English: variant of   Massey  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":7,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":20,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":74,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bibl